ue":-1.72,"unit":"% YoY","status":"weak","read":"Profit down 2% YoY (latest TTM).","meaning":"Trailing-twelve-month net profit vs the year-ago TTM (and whether the YoY rate is rising = 'accelerating').","why_useful":"Improving, accelerating earnings tend to drive re-rating; falling profit warns of a deteriorating business.","why_it_can_fail":"TTM can be lumpy for cyclicals/one-offs; cross-check the multi-year trend on the Fundamentals tab."}]},"valuation":{"ok":true,"is_bank":false,"pe_now":30.9,"pe_percentile":35.0,"median_pe":32.7,"earnings_yield_pct":3.24,"pb":4.08,"ev_ebitda":20.95,"quality_score":92.0,"pat_cagr_5y_pct":21.9,"peg":1.41,"cheapness":{"status":"ok","read":"P/E at the 35-percentile of its 10-yr range \u2014 mid-range vs its own history."},"expectations":"At 30.9\u00d7 earnings for ~22% 5-yr profit CAGR, the market is paying \u22481.41\u00d7 growth (PEG). >2 = a lot already priced in; <1 = cheap if growth holds.","cyclical_caveat":null,"meaning":"P/E percentile = where today's price-to-earnings sits within the stock's own last-10-yr range (low = cheap vs its past). Paired with the Quality score and 5-yr profit growth so a cheap multiple is judged against business strength, not in isolation.","why_useful":"Cheapness only matters relative to quality and growth \u2014 a low P/E on a declining or peak-cyclical business is a trap, not a bargain.","why_it_can_fail":"P/E breaks for loss-makers / one-offs; for banks use P/B not EV/EBITDA; a multiple cheap vs history can stay cheap if the business has structurally de-rated."},"ownership":{"ok":true,"na":null,"holders":{"FII":{"periods":["Jun 2024","Sep 2024","Dec 2024","Mar 2025","Jun 2025","Sep 2025","Dec 2025","Mar 2026"],"values":[3.79,4.82,5.03,5.24,10.04,11.3,11.48,10.27],"latest_pct":10.27,"chg_1y_pp":5.03},"DII":{"periods":["Jun 2024","Sep 2024","Dec 2024","Mar 2025","Jun 2025","Sep 2025","Dec 2025","Mar 2026"],"values":[3.84,3.17,3.99,4.96,7.2,6.95,8.06,8.29],"latest_pct":8.29,"chg_1y_pp":3.33},"Publi